<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-769-724  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 769 724.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 20 1990 v24 n34 p29(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A 4M-bit DRAM come true. (dynamic random access memory)(SystemIndustries Megaram-SDI disk drive)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnson, Maryfran.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>System Industries introduces a new storage module for itsMegaram-SDI disk drive.andP;  The 128Mbyte module uses dynamic randomaccess memory (DRAM) technology to quadruple the storage capacityof a single quad-size board for a maximum capacity of 2Gbytes persystem.andP;  The module is positioned against DEC's ESE20 solid-statedisk which costs $916 per megabyte.andP;  The System Industries moduleis priced at $577 per megabyte.andP;  The price of the Megaram-SDI wascut 26 percent and can be purchased for $73,900.andP;  Lashco Inc, aChicago-based stock trading company, experienced a 150 percentimprovement in throughput for on-line transaction processing byusing the new Megaram-SDI disk system with its DEC VAX 8550.andP;  Theprice difference between the DEC and System Industries disks maynot be particularly significant because the media is priceyanyway.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   System Industries Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    SYI.andO;Product:   System Industries MegaRam-SDI (Disk drive) (product enhancement).andO;Topic:     EnhancementsDisk DrivesDRAM.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>